	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Well, I think no one was stupid enough to suggest a mage should tank for the pet. There was one comment that you should keep a close look at your pet's health during a fight, so you won't suddenly get your hands full with an angry mob bashing your frail body to bits. If your Channeling skill isn't really good, you will find you must hit the mob to death, often a cumbersome task for a mage, since we are really bad weapon wielders. With the new &quot;/pet report health&quot; command as a hot key, you can easily keep track how your pet is doing, and, if it is getting critical, step in and take some damage to avoid a pet death.<BR>
<BR>
A very common mistake among all pure casters is hitting the mob right away with some big damage spells. The more intelligent critters will be on your throat in a second, and even your pet will have a hard time taunting it off you. Play it cool at first, and aim rather for that final blow before it starts running away from you.<BR>
<BR>
The most fun is of course playing with a group, where your capabilities to summon dimensional pockets, food, water, bandages, heatstones, arrows, etc, etc, will be very appreciated by your companions.<BR>
<BR>
Tip: In the earlier levels, try to keep up all your different casting skills, you will need them all badly later on. I had to spell myself for hours getting my Evocation skill up after not using it for many levels. Tedious and boring(although it helped raise my bind wound skill alot ;-).<BR>
<BR>
Tip II: At level 30 I discovered that a beer or two may give you as much as one bbl mana back. This could be very useful if you suddenly find yourself outnumbered and OOM, and desperately need to gate out of a battle!
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
